A TWISTED thief raided a city barber shop before setting fire to the building, the Evening Times can reveal.&nbsp;Cops are investigating whether an &quot;opportunist&quot; robber broke into the Turkish barber shop in Glasgow city centreAs revealed by the Evening Times, Gogo's barbers in Cambridge Street was torched in a late-night attack on Sunday.Police revealed the blaze, which swept through the barber shop in Cambridge Street, had been started deliberately.They are now investigating the possibility that a raider broke in and then set the premises alight.A source said officers were still working to establish if anything had been taken from the barbers, which has been left badly damaged by smoke.Neighbours raised the alarm after smoke was spotted coming from the premises shortly before 10pm on Sunday.Detective Sergeant Alister Thom, who is leading the investigation, said: &quot;This was a dangerous act and could easily have resulted in a more serious outcome.&quot;Our investigations are at early stage but I am keen to speak to a male seen in the area shortly before the fire was reported.&quot;He is described as between 40 and 50-years-old with a stocky build and wearing an orange puffa jacket with a white T-shirt and blue jeans.&quot;I would ask this man or anyone who saw him, or anything else suspicious, to contact police.&quot;Witnesses who may have seen the man loitering near the barber shop before 10pm on Sunday have been urged to come forward.Residents from seven flats above the shop had to be evacuated as the fire was brought under control.A Scottish Fire and Rescue spokesman said: &quot;We received a 999 call shortly after 9.50pm reporting a fire in a shop beneath flats in Cambridge Street.&quot;Two crews were immediately sent from Cowcaddens along with two more from Maryhill and firefighters reached the scene three minutes later.&quot;A team of two entered the property in breathing apparatus and extinguished the fire using a main jet.&quot;Our crews used a positive pressure ventilation fan to clear smoke from the premises and checked for any hidden fire spread by cutting away and using a thermal imaging camera.&quot;Officers from our specialist fire investigation unit attended and will work closely with police to establish the circumstances surrounding the fire.&quot;Anyone with any information about the fire is asked to contact Police Scotland on 101.